We have already noted that South Africa and Russia are examples of countries that are not close to the equator but are characterized by relatively high levels of aggression and violence. But at the level of within-country comparisons, aggression and violence levels are higher in the south than in the north. Italy and the United States are prime examples. Southern Italy is dominated by mafia-related terror and violence, and many southern states in the US are characterized by a “culture of honor” that is often defended through aggression and violence (
 Nisbett, 1993; 
 Nisbett & Cohen, 1996).
